President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring April 14, 2011, as Pan American Day and April 10-16, 2011, as Pan American Week. The proclamation highlights the close partnerships and bonds between the countries of the Americas, emphasizing the region's democratic and peaceful nature. It celebrates milestones such as the establishment of the Organization of American States and the recognition of the International Year for People of African Descent. The proclamation acknowledges the challenges faced by the region, including poverty, lack of economic opportunity, and human rights violations. It calls for continued cooperation and partnership to overcome these challenges and build a safer and more prosperous future. The proclamation urges the governors and officials of the United States to honor these observances with appropriate ceremonies and activities.